fields.description:
Currently capabilities can be shared between all local agents as well as between all remote agents. As [this documentation|https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/BAMBOO/Defining+a+new+executable+capability] states:
{quote}
Shared remote executable capabilities are not shared with elastic agents.
{quote}

This is particularly detrimental to OnDemand customers as they can only utilize Elastic Agents making shared capabilities mostly useless to OnDemand users.

{{setenv.sh}} starts with the following comment:
{noformat}
# One way to set the Bamboo HOME path is here via this variable.  Simply uncomment it and set a valid path like /bamboo/home.  You can of course set it outside in the command terminal.  That will also work.
#
#BAMBOO_HOME=""
{noformat}

However, setting {{BAMBOO_HOME}} here has no effect.
The proper place is the {{bamboo-init.properties}}, as described in the documentation.

The note in {{bamboo-init.properties}} is also incorrect:
{noformat}
## You can specify your bamboo.home property here or in your system environment variables.
{noformat}

All the other Java-based Atlassian products (JIRA, Confluence, Stash, etc) support setting the app home with environment variables.

If the Build log takes too long to load in the Build Result view the 'Download Log' and 'View Log' options will not be rendered. 

The log can still be reached by using the Direct URL: 
For example: {{/download/PROJECTKEY-PLANKEY-JOB1/build_logs/PROJECTKEY-PLANKEY-JOB1-34.log}}

When creating global, project or plan specific variables, provide a way to mark then as sensitive. When marked as such, obfuscate the values in the logs.  

I have a Visual Studio Solution which publishes NuGet packages to a NuGet repository.  In order to achieve that, my build steps call the appropriate NuGet command with a key, that is suppose to be "secret" to a selective few folks.  However, the key appears in the logs, which means that anyone with access to logs can use it to publish their own packages.  This causes some issues for compliance etc.  Its even worse for projects that are open source and any anonymous user has access to the logs. 

So lets assume my API key is 6c7b0000-0000-0000-0000-611090000000. Instead of this being shown in the logs

{code:title=project.txt|borderStyle=solid}
The command ""C:\Users\bamboo\bamboo-home\xml-data\build-dir\CAC-CMB-JOB1\build\\NuGet.exe" push "" -ApiKey "6c7b0000-0000-0000-0000-611090000000"" exited with code 1.
{code}

It would display

{code:title=project.txt|borderStyle=solid}
The command ""C:\Users\bamboo\bamboo-home\xml-data\build-dir\CAC-CMB-JOB1\build\\NuGet.exe" push "" -ApiKey "##########"" exited with code 1.
{code}

For security reasons the masked variable should not match the length of the actual sensitive data.  Always create it with a fixed length (say 10 characters).  Someone can infer which value was used by the length.

Someone may argue that its best to create a Bamboo task to do the work; and ensure sensitive data is not in the log,  I'd argue that for the sake of maintenance and portability, such tasks may always be defined in a build script.

At the moment:
{code:title=com/atlassian/utils/process/ExternalProcess.java}
...
DEFAULT_UNIX_EXECUTOR = "/bin/sh";
...
{code}
Users will have spent a not inconsiderable amount of time setting up a user to run the bamboo agent with specific needs (RVM comes to mind but there are other examples) it would seem logical to invoke a non-interactive login shell would solve this issue.
{panel}
/bin/sh -l
{panel}

This issue is separate to being able to choose the shell that is invoked.

Bamboo reports that the build log size is {{70224kb}}:
{noformat}
2014-06-24 11:00:05,935 INFO [http-bio-8085-exec-2] [AccessLogFilter] tappy GET https://my.company.com/bamboo/download/ABC-DE14-JOB1/build_logs/ABC-DE14-JOB1-184.log 70224kb
{noformat}

However, the log size is only {{478kb}} big.
